  "prompt": "Can a foreign citizen open a savings bank account, in India?",
  "response": "Yes, a foreign citizen can open a savings bank account in India, but there are specific requirements and conditions that need to be met. Generally, foreign citizens can open Non-Resident Ordinary (NRO) accounts or Non-Resident External (NRE) accounts. Here are the key points:\n\n1. **NRO (Non-Resident Ordinary) Account:** \n    - This account type can be used to manage income earned in India, such as rent, dividends, pensions, and interest.\n    - Money deposited in an NRO account is subject to tax in India.\n\n2. **NRE (Non-Resident External) Account:**\n    - This account type is useful for managing income earned outside of India and can be fully repatriated.\n    - Funds in an NRE account are not subject to tax in India.\n\nTo open these accounts, foreign citizens need to provide certain documents:\n\n1. Proof of identity (passport, visa).\n2. Proof of address (overseas and Indian address if applicable).\n3. Photographs.\n4. Application form provided by the bank.\n\nAdditionally, banks may require various declarations and may have specific procedures. It's wise to contact the bank directly for precise documentation requirements and account terms, as these can vary between institutions.",
